---
// Static, hand-written methodology page — the trust anchor every Insights page
// links to (hard constraint #6). Evergreen; no pipeline data.
import InsightsLayout from '../../components/insights/InsightsLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/seo/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import FAQSchema from '../../components/seo/FAQSchema.astro';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'What is the difference between obligations and outlays?',
    answer:
      'An obligation is money the government has legally committed on an award; an outlay is money actually disbursed. GovHub Insights reports obligations, which are the standard measure of contract award activity. Outlays can lag obligations by months or years.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Where does GovHub Insights data come from?',
    answer:
      'All figures come from USAspending.gov, the U.S. government’s official open-data source for federal awards, retrieved through its public API. GovHub analyzes and republishes the data; the underlying records are U.S. federal public domain.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Why do current fiscal-year totals look lower than last year?',
    answer:
      'Current-year figures cover the fiscal year to date — a partial year — so they are compared against a completed prior year. A partial year will almost always show a lower total until the year closes on September 30.',
  },
];
---

<InsightsLayout
  title="Methodology — GovHub Insights"
  description="How GovHub Insights builds federal contract market data: sources, definitions (obligations vs. outlays), fiscal-year windows, and known reporting caveats."
>
  <Breadcrumbs
    items={[
      { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
      { name: 'Insights', url: '/insights/' },
      { name: 'Methodology', url: '/insights/methodology/' },
    ]}
  />

  <article class="prose methodology">
    <p class="eyebrow">GovHub Insights</p>
    <h1>Methodology</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      GovHub Insights turns public federal spending records into readable market intelligence. This
      page explains exactly what the numbers mean, where they come from, and where their limits are —
      so you can cite them with confidence.
    </p>

    <h2>Source</h2>
    <p>
      Every figure on GovHub Insights is derived from <a href="https://www.usaspending.gov" rel="noopener" target="_blank">USAspending.gov</a>,
      the U.S. government's official source of record for federal award data, retrieved through its
      public API. The underlying data is U.S. federal government public domain. GovHub analyzes,
      aggregates, and republishes it; we do not alter the underlying records.
    </p>

    <h2>What we count</h2>
    <p>
      Unless a page states otherwise, all figures are contract <strong>obligations</strong> on
      definitive contracts — federal award types A, B, C, and D. We exclude grants, loans, direct
      payments, and indefinite-delivery vehicles (IDVs) so that "contract spending" means what
      contractors expect it to mean: dollars committed to buy goods and services.
    </p>

    <h2>Obligations, outlays, and ceilings</h2>
    <p>
      These three are not interchangeable. An <strong>obligation</strong> is money the government has
      legally committed on an award. An <strong>outlay</strong> is money actually paid out, which can
      lag obligations by months or years. A contract <strong>ceiling</strong> is the maximum an award
      could reach, not what has been committed. GovHub Insights reports obligations, the standard
      measure of award activity.
    </p>

    <h2>Fiscal years and "to date"</h2>
    <p>
      The federal fiscal year runs October 1 through September 30 — FY2026 began October 1, 2025.
      Current-year totals are labeled "FY-to-date" and reflect only the portion of the year that has
      been reported. Because a partial year is compared against a completed prior year, year-over-year
      changes for the current year understate the eventual full-year figure and should be read as a
      running comparison, not a final one.
    </p>

    <h2>Vendor names</h2>
    <p>
      Federal recipient data is messy: the same company can appear under subsidiaries, DBA names, and
      recipient hierarchies. We use USAspending's own recipient aggregation as-is and link vendor names
      to their USAspending recipient profiles rather than attempting our own entity resolution, so you
      can always trace a number back to its source.
    </p>

    <h2>Reporting lag</h2>
    <p>
      Agencies report transactions on a delay; the Department of Defense in particular reports to the
      federal system on roughly a 90-day lag. Recent-period figures therefore undercount activity,
      especially for DoD, and are best read as "newly reported" rather than complete.
    </p>

    <h2>Which entities get a page</h2>
    <p>
      To avoid thin, low-signal pages, GovHub Insights builds a dedicated dashboard for an entity only
      when it clears meaningful volume thresholds in obligations, award count, and years of available
      trend data. Smaller entities still appear in ranking tables but do not get a standalone page.
    </p>

    <h2>Updates</h2>
    <p>
      Evergreen dashboards refresh on a weekly cadence, and each page shows the date its data was last
      current. If a refresh fails, the site keeps serving the last good dataset rather than publishing
      partial numbers.
    </p>

    <h2>Attribution</h2>
    <p>
      Source: USAspending.gov data, analyzed by GovHub. You are welcome to cite, link, and embed these
      charts; embedded charts carry an automatic link back to their source page.
    </p>
  </article>

  <FAQSchema faqs={faqs} />
</InsightsLayout>

<style>
  .methodology {
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
  }
  .methodology h1 {
    margin: 0.25rem 0 0.75rem;
  }
  .methodology h2 {
    margin-top: 2.25rem;
  }
  .methodology .lede {
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
  }
  .methodology p {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
  }
</style>
